40|$|The {{auditing}} profession has been criticised that <b>auditing</b> <b>standards</b> favour the self-interests {{of a limited}} number of members or certain constituencies of society and not society at large. As auditing is a means of social accountability, all social constituencies have a legitimate interest in defining what is termed as generally accepted <b>auditing</b> <b>standards.</b> The state would undertake the regulatory function of <b>auditing</b> <b>standard</b> setting itself, {{were it not for the}} processes administered and managed by the self-regulating bodies. <b>Auditing</b> <b>standards</b> are therefore supplementary to legislation and can be described as quasi-legislatory. This paper examines the <b>auditing</b> <b>standard</b> setting process in South Africa and points to certain shortcomings which challenge the regulators' claims of legitimacy...|$|R
